summary.content:
Description: A frontal system affecting the North Coast this morning is bringing milder air along with some precipitation. Cold air trapped in the Skeena River valley combined with warm air aloft will bring local freezing rain in the Terrace to Kitimat corridor through this morning. The freezing precipitation is expected to change to rain near noon when temperatures finally rise above the freezing mark. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas. Freezing Rain Warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please monitor local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to pacificstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #BCStorm.

Description: Un système frontal affectant la côte nord ce matin apporte de l'air plus doux et un peu de précipitations. L'air froid emprisonne dans la vallée de la rivière Skeena et l'air chaud en altitude occasionneront de la pluie verglaçante par endroits entré Terrace et Kitimat ce matin. Les précipitations verglaçantes devraient se changer en pluie vers midi lorsque les températures grimperont finalement au-dessus du point de congélation. Les surfaces, comme les routes, les rues, les trottoirs et les terrains de stationnement, deviendront glacées, glissantes et dangereuses. Faites preuve de prudence lorsque vous marchez ou conduisez dans les secteurs touchés. Un avertissement de pluie verglaçante est émis lorsque de la pluie tombe pendant que les températures sont inférieures à zéro, ce qui occasionnera des accumulations de verglas. Les météorologistes d'Environnement Canada mettront les alertes à jour au besoin. Informez-vous auprès des médias ou écoutez Radiométéo. Pour signaler du temps violent, vous pouvez envoyer un courriel à pacificstorm@ec.gc.ca ou un gazouillis à #BCMétéo.

Description: Lows of near minus 30 combined with light to moderate winds are producing extremely cold wind chill values near minus 40 early this morning. While anyone who isn't dressed warmly is at risk in cold weather conditions, some are at greater risk than others for frost bite and hypothermia: - homeless people - outdoor workers - people living in homes that are poorly insulated (with no heat or no power) - people with certain medical conditions such as diabetes, peripheral neuropathy and diseases affecting the blood vessels, people taking certain medications including beta-blockers - winter sport enthusiasts - people who consume excess alcohol - infants and - seniors. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.

Description: A very cold airmass has settled across much of southern Ontario. This cold air combined with light to moderate northerly winds is resulting in wind chill values near minus 30 early this morning. While anyone who isn't dressed warmly is at risk in cold weather conditions, some are at greater risk than others for frost bite and hypothermia: - homeless people - outdoor workers - people living in homes that are poorly insulated (with no heat or no power) - people with certain medical conditions such as diabetes, peripheral neuropathy and diseases affecting the blood vessels, people taking certain medications including beta-blockers - winter sport enthusiasts - people who consume excess alcohol - infants and - seniors. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.

Description: A very cold airmass is settling across much of southern Ontario tonight. This cold air combined with moderate northerly winds will result in wind chill values near minus 30 early this morning. While anyone who isn't dressed warmly is at risk in cold weather conditions, some are at greater risk than others for frost bite and hypothermia: - homeless people - outdoor workers - people living in homes that are poorly insulated (with no heat or no power) - people with certain medical conditions such as diabetes, peripheral neuropathy and diseases affecting the blood vessels, people taking certain medications including beta-blockers - winter sport enthusiasts - people who consume excess alcohol - infants and - seniors. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.

Description: Une masse d'air très froid s'installe sur une bonne partie du sud de l'Ontario cette nuit. Portez des vêtements appropriés. - Portez toujours des vêtements adaptés au temps qu'il fait. Les tissus synthétiques et la laine fournissent une meilleure isolation. Certains tissus synthétiques sont conçus pour éloigner la transpiration du corps, ce qui vous garde au sec et réduit davantage les risques. - Habillez-vous de plusieurs couches de vêtements, dont une couche extérieure étanche au vent. Description: A very cold airmass will settle across much of southern Ontario tonight. This cold air combined with winds of up to 15 km/h will result in wind chill values near minus 30 early this morning. While anyone who isn't dressed warmly is at risk in cold weather conditions, some are at greater risk than others for frost bite and hypothermia: - homeless people - outdoor workers - people living in homes that are poorly insulated (with no heat or no power) - people with certain medical conditions such as diabetes, peripheral neuropathy and diseases affecting the blood vessels, people taking certain medications including beta-blockers - winter sport enthusiasts - people who consume excess alcohol - infants and - seniors. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.

Même si le froid menace toute personne qui n'est pas habillée chaudement, certaines personnes risquent davantage de souffrir d'engelures et d'hypothermie : - les sans-abri - les personnes travaillant à l'extérieur - les personnes habitant des maisons mal isolées (sans chauffage ou sans électricité) - les personnes atteintes de certains problèmes médicaux comme le diabète, les neuropathies périphériques et les affections des vaisseaux sanguins, les personnes prenant certains médicaments, notamment des bêta-bloquants - les amateurs de sports d'hiver - les personnes qui ont une consommation excessive d'alcool - les nourrissons et - les personnes âgées. Portez des vêtements appropriés. - Portez toujours des vêtements adaptés au temps qu'il fait. Les tissus synthétiques et la laine fournissent une meilleure isolation. Certains tissus synthétiques sont conçus pour éloigner la transpiration du corps, ce qui vous garde au sec et réduit davantage les risques. - Habillez-vous de plusieurs couches de vêtements, dont une couche extérieure étanche au vent. Vous pouvez toujours retirer ou ajouter une couche selon que vous avez trop chaud (avant de commencer à transpirer) ou que vous avez froid. - Portez des chaussettes chaudes, des gants, un chapeau et un foulard par temps froid. N'oubliez pas de couvrir votre nez. - Si vous êtes mouillé, changez-vous dès que possible, car vous perdrez rapidement de la chaleur autrement. Un avertissement de froid extrême est émis lorsque le refroidissement éolien ou les températures très froides présentent un danger élevé pour la santé (engelure, hypothermie, etc.). Les météorologistes d'Environnement Canada mettront les alertes à jour au besoin. Informez-vous auprès des médias ou de Radiométéo. Pour signaler du temps violent, vous pouvez envoyer un courriel à storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca ou un gazouillis à #ONMétéo.

Description: A frontal system affecting the North Coast this evening will bring variable precipitation types across North Coast - Inland sections. summary.content:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. For western Labrador wind chill values of minus 45 or colder can be expected overnight and Tuesday morning. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Stay up to date with Weatheradio or your local media. Email reports of severe weather to weatherNLWO@ec.gc.ca or call 1-877-815-9900. You may tweet reports using the hashtag #NLwx.

Description: Un épisode pendant lequel le refroidissement éolien sera très élevé est prévu. Sur l'ouest du Labrador, un refroidissement éolien de moins 45 ou plus froid est attendu au cours de la nuit et mardi matin. Portez des vêtements appropriés. - Portez toujours des vêtements adaptés au temps qu'il fait. Les tissus synthétiques et la laine fournissent une meilleure isolation. Certains tissus synthétiques sont conçus pour éloigner la transpiration du corps, ce qui vous garde au sec et réduit davantage les risques. - Habillez-vous de plusieurs couches de vêtements, dont une couche extérieure étanche au vent. Vous pouvez toujours retirer ou ajouter une couche selon que vous avez trop chaud (avant de commencer à transpirer) ou que vous avez froid. - Portez des chaussettes chaudes, des gants, un chapeau et un foulard par temps froid. N'oubliez pas de couvrir votre nez. - Si vous êtes mouillé, changez-vous dès que possible, car vous perdrez rapidement de la chaleur autrement. Un avertissement de froid extrême est émis lorsque le refroidissement éolien ou les températures très froides présentent un danger élevé pour la santé (engelure, hypothermie, etc.). Description: Areas of freezing drizzle are expected or occuring. A system affecting the north coast this evening will bring variable precipitation across North Coast - Inland Sections. Cold air trapped in the Skeena valley combined with warm air aloft will bring freezing drizzle to Terrace tonight until Tuesday morning. As precipitation intensity increases, there is a risk freezing drizzle could transition into a period of freezing rain. Please stay tuned. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing drizzle can produce thin, hard to detect layers of ice. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas. Weather Advisories for Freezing Drizzle are issued when drizzle falling in sub zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please monitor local media or Weatheradio. Description: Lows of near minus 30 combined with winds up to 15 km/h are expected to produce extremely cold wind chill values near minus 40 later tonight and early Tuesday morning. While anyone who isn't dressed warmly is at risk in cold weather conditions, some are at greater risk than others for frost bite and hypothermia: - homeless people - outdoor workers - people living in homes that are poorly insulated (with no heat or no power) - people with certain medical conditions such as diabetes, peripheral neuropathy and diseases affecting the blood vessels, people taking certain medications including beta-blockers - winter sport enthusiasts - people who consume excess alcohol - infants and - seniors. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.

Portez des vêtements appropriés. - Portez toujours des vêtements adaptés au temps qu'il fait. Les tissus synthétiques et la laine fournissent une meilleure isolation. Description: Un épisode pendant lequel le refroidissement éolien sera très élevé est prévu. La combinaison d'une masse d'air arctique et de vents d'ouest causera du refroidissement éolien extrême sur plusieurs régions du nord de la province la nuit prochaine. Portez des vêtements appropriés. - Portez toujours des vêtements adaptés au temps qu'il fait. Les tissus synthétiques et la laine fournissent une meilleure isolation. Certains tissus synthétiques sont conçus pour éloigner la transpiration du corps, ce qui vous garde au sec et réduit davantage les risques. - Habillez-vous de plusieurs couches de vêtements, dont une couche extérieure étanche au vent. Vous pouvez toujours retirer ou ajouter une couche selon que vous avez trop chaud (avant de commencer à transpirer) ou que vous avez froid. - Portez des chaussettes chaudes, des gants, un chapeau et un foulard par temps froid. N'oubliez pas de couvrir votre nez. - Si vous êtes mouillé, changez-vous dès que possible, car vous perdrez rapidement de la chaleur autrement. Un avertissement de froid extrême est émis lorsque le refroidissement éolien ou les températures très froides présentent un danger élevé pour la santé (engelure, hypothermie, etc.). Les météorologistes d'Environnement Canada mettront les alertes à jour au besoin. Veuillez vous informer auprès des médias ou de Radiométéo pour obtenir les mises à jour. Pour signaler du temps violent, composez le 1-800-361-0233 ou envoyez un courriel à tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. Vous pouvez également le faire en envoyant des gazouillis à #météoqc.

Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An Arctic air mass and westerly winds will give extreme wind chill values in several areas of Northern Quebec overnight tonight. Wear appropriate clothing. - Always wear clothing appropriate for the weather. Synthetic and wool fabrics provide better insulation. Some synthetic fabrics are designed to keep perspiration away from your body which keep you dry and further reduce your risk. - Dress in layers with a wind resistant outer layer. You can remove layers if you get too warm (before you start sweating) or add a layer if you get cold. - Wear warm socks, gloves, a hat and scarf in cold weather. Be sure to cover your nose to protect it. - If you get wet, change into dry clothing as soon as possible. You lose heat faster when you're wet. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-361-0233 or send an email to tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. You may also tweet reports of severe weather to #meteoqc.
